<p><strong>California Mouse(<em>Peromyscus californicus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Cricetidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Peromyscus californicus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong> California Mouse<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The California Mouse has a length of 3⅘-4⅗ inches, a tail length of 5-5⅘ inches, and a weight of 42-50 grams. It is the largest mouse of the genus, has a dark brown color, blackish top of tail, whitish feet and belly, and large ears. Its size alone is enough to distinguish this mouse from other mice. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=california%20mouse&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=2" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This mouse can be found in slopes grown with live oaks and dense chaparral. It eats fruits, seeds, and flowers of shrubs, small insects, fungi, and berries. It stores acorns in nests that are often in houses of Dusky-footed Woodrats, and also uses buildings for nesting sites. Nests consist of twigs and sticks, lined with fine grasses. It bears 1-3 young several times a year.</p>
